    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-01-27T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-01-27T06:00:00-05:00" n="36"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                <head>36. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Vietnam</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d36fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751K.00/1-2762. Secret; Priority; Eyes Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1962-01-27T19:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1962—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>980. Refs: <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 907 and <gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 963.<note n="2" xml:id="d36fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d33fn2">Document 33 and footnote 2</ref> thereto.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NDT2">Thuan</persName> told me today he had taken up with
                    President <persName corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName> question new U.S. Military
                    Assistance Command; said he had explained idea to <persName corresp="#p_NDD2"
                        >Diem</persName> thoroughly; that President wanted to see me about it. I
                    asked whether there were any particular questions or problems in his mind.
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDT2">Thuan</persName> said the only problem that
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName> seemed to have was whether the
                    U.S. Mission in Viet-Nam was to have “one or more heads”. He said from point of
                    view <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> it was essential that U.S. activities
                    should head up to one person in Viet-Nam. I told <persName corresp="#p_NDT2"
                        >Thuan</persName> that President <persName corresp="#p_NDD2">Diem</persName>
                    need have no <pb facs="0086" n="66" xml:id="pg_66"/> concern on this score; as
                    to details, this was a matter of internal U.S. arrangements which would, I felt
                    sure, work satisfactorily from <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                    standpoint.</p>
                <p>I have been waiting for ten days for clarification of matter referred to in
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 898.<note n="3" xml:id="d36fn3"
                        >See <ref target="#d33fn3">footnote 3, Document 33</ref>.</note> Pouched
                    message not yet received, and next pouch due late January 30th. I need to be in
                    a position to speak with assurance to <persName corresp="#p_NDD2"
                        >Diem</persName> on any questions he may raise in connection with new
                    command set-up and would appreciate, if possible, telegraphic summary contents
                    pouched message. Needless to say, I have not raised with <gloss target="#t_GVN1"
                        >GVN</gloss>, nor with anyone here, question of internal U.S.
                    relationships.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NFEJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Nolting</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
